******
[2]
Date: 25 Nov 2016
Source: Calgary Herald [edited]
http://calgaryherald.com/storyline/bovine-tb-cfia-will-allow-quarantined-cattle-to-be-moved-to-approved-feedlot-site


The Canadian Food Inspection Agency [CFIA] has approved a plan that would allow ranchers affected by the bovine tuberculosis outbreak in south east Alberta to move their cattle off their properties. The food safety watchdog said on Friday [25 Nov 2016] that it has given the go-ahead to a beef industry proposal to establish a feedlot as an alternate quarantine site, a move that would give some relief to the ranchers who have said their properties are not set up to feed and water quarantined cattle over the winter months.

A total of 35 ranches (31 in south east Alberta and 4 in south west Saskatchewan) are currently prevented from moving their animals while the CFIA conducts an investigation into an outbreak of bovine TB. Six confirmed cases have been found so far and linked to a single herd near Jenner, Alberta.

Dr Jaspinder Komal, the CFIA's deputy chief veterinary officer, said it will be up to the beef industry to find an available feedlot. He said if all goes as planned, cattle could begin to be moved to the approved location as early as Monday or Tuesday [28-29 Nov 2016] next week. "This feedlot option ensures that the quarantine is maintained and that appropriate biosecurity measures are in place to control the risk of disease exposure for other animals," Komal said.

The move was applauded by beef industry representatives, who have been lobbying for an alternate quarantine site to lift the pressure off ranchers who had expected to sell their calves earlier this fall [2016] and aren't prepared to winter them. Approximately 22 000 cattle are currently affected by the CFIA quarantine. "It'll make a big difference to these guys to get the calves out of the way," said Alberta Beef Producers chair Bob Lowe. "There's going to be people starting calving while this quarantine is still going on. So to be able to get this current calf crop out of the way is just going to make a big difference to their emotional state." It's not clear yet who will pay to feed and house the quarantined cattle at the approved feedlot. Lowe said he is hopeful a disaster relief funding package, expected to be announced as early as next week, will go a long way toward helping ranchers cover the expense.

Though details have yet to be announced, federal agriculture minister Lawrence MacAulay said in the House of Commons on Thursday [24 Nov 2016] that the government is considering all options to help ranchers under quarantine as a result of the discovery of 6 cases of bovine TB near Jenner, Alberta. He said discussions are taking place with the governments of Alberta and Saskatchewan to expedite an aid package. "The minister committed to working with his provincial counterparts as quickly as possible to cover extra costs faced by producers experiencing income declines due to bovine TB," said Guy Gallant, spokesperson for the minister, in an email on Friday [25 Nov 2016]. "This would help provide financial assistance for extraordinary costs such as interest costs on loans due to the circumstances."

Though the CFIA compensates producers whose animals have to be destroyed as a result of an investigation, it doesn't provide compensation for losses incurred as a result of being unable to get healthy animals to the feedlot or auction block because of a quarantine. Nor does it compensate producers for being forced to hold onto and feed their calves over the winter months while the investigation continues.

The province of Alberta has made a formal request to the federal government, under the terms of the AgriRecovery Framework, for assistance for producers affected by the bovine TB quarantine. AgriRecovery is a federal-provincial program designed to help producers recover extraordinary costs in the event of a disaster, beyond what is available through other financial assistance programs.

In an interview, provincial Agriculture Minister Oneil Carlier said he was encouraged to hear his federal counterpart suggest an announcement is forthcoming. "To be able to have this in place relatively soon is great news. ... I'm hoping perhaps as early as next week we'll have those details finalized and be able to move forward," Carlier said.

Bovine TB is a reportable disease in Canada and has been subject to a mandatory national eradication program since 1923. While Canada is considered to be officially free of bovine TB, isolated cases still occasionally occur. The latest bovine TB cases are not expected to affect border access for Canadian beef. Incidences of bovine TB generally pose very little risk to public health.

[byline: Amanda Stephenson]

